nment in countries around the globe. The authors focus on the need to move beyond emergency relief to create new social and economic structures that can serve as the foundations for a lasting peace. Prosperity, the authors acknowledge, does not guarantee peace; but a lack of economic development will almost certainly lead to renewed violence. This conviction informs their thorough discussion of the policy dilemmas confronted in postconflict situations and a range of concrete, successful approaches to resolving them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aBijlsma, Martijn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorgh, Chris van der, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Richard H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrynen, Rex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChowdhury, Abdur R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDegu, Wondem Asres, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanlon, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerrero, Jose Luis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHohe, Tanja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoward, Ross, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJunne, Gerd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJunne, Gerd, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKamphuis, Bertine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurshed, S. Mansoob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPlunkett, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4http